def merge(intervals):
    intervals.sort(key=lambda x: x[0])
    merged = []
    for start, end in intervals:
        if merged and start <= merged[-1][1]:
            merged[-1][1] = max(merged[-1][1], end)
        else:
            merged.append([start, end])
    return merged
Sort by start time first, then sweep once: if the current interval's start is <= the last merged interval's end, they overlap, so extend the last interval's end; otherwise start a new interval. O(n log n) time, dominated by the sort.

